==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Turquois
<hw>Tur*quois"</hw> }</mhw> <pr>(?;
277)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>turquoise</ets>; cf. Pr. & Sp.
<ets>turquesa</ets>, It. <ets>turchese</ets>, <ets>turchina</ets>, LL.
<ets>turchesius</ets>, <ets>turchina</ets>; -- so called because first
brought from <ets>Turkey</ets>. See 1st <er>Turkey</er>.]</ety>
<fld>(Min.)</fld> <def>A hydrous phosphate of alumina containing a
little copper; calaite. It has a blue, or bluish green, color, and
usually occurs in reniform masses with a botryoidal surface.</def>
<altsp>[Formerly written also <asp>turcois</asp>, and
<asp>turkois</asp>.]</altsp>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ Turquoise is susceptible of a high polish, and when of a
bright blue color is much esteemed as a gem. The finest specimens come
from Persia. It is also found in New Mexico and Arizona, and is regarded
as identical with the <xex>chalchihuitl</xex> of the
Mexicans.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Turquoise</ent>⟦br⟧
